    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w34260</id>
    <title>Test-Optional College Admissions: ACT and SAT Scores, Applications, and Enrollment Changes</title>
    <updated>2025-09-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Christopher Avery, Lena Shi &amp; Preston Magouirk</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This paper uses data from the largest college application platform in the U.S. to describe application and enrollment changes in response to widespread test-optional admissions adoption between 2018-2021. Although test-optional policies aimed to expand college access, underrepresented students did not apply to Elite colleges at higher rates and Elite colleges still received large numbers of high-scoring applications after tests became optional. Despite the oversupply of high-scoring applicants in the test-optional period, Elite colleges enrolled more lower-scorers with high grades, in particular first-generation and lower-income students. Enrollment in less selective colleges also increased among high-scorers, so test-optional policies may exacerbate undermatching.</content>
